    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>A common emitter amplifier has a voltage gain of 50 an input impedance of 100 $$\\Omega$$ and an output impedance of 400 $$\\Omega$$. The power gain of the amplifier is</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "500"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "1000"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "625"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "50"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>To find the power gain of the amplifier, we first need to understand the relationship between voltage gain, input impedance, and output impedance.</p>\n\n<p>The power gain (G<sub>P</sub>) of an amplifier is given by the product of the voltage gain (G<sub>V</sub>) and the current gain (G<sub>I</sub>). However, we can derive it directly from the voltage gain and the impedance values.</p>\n\n<p>Given:</p>\n\n<p>Voltage gain (G<sub>V</sub>) = 50</p>\n\n<p>Input impedance (R<sub>in</sub>) = 100 $$\\Omega$$</p>\n\n<p>Output impedance (R<sub>out</sub>) = 400 $$\\Omega$$</p>\n\n<p>We know that:</p>\n\n<p>$$ G_P = \\frac{V_{out}^2 / R_{out}}{V_{in}^2 / R_{in}} $$</p>\n\n<p>Since the voltage gain is:</p>\n\n<p>$$ G_V = \\frac{V_{out}}{V_{in}} = 50 $$</p>\n\n<p>Substituting $$ G_V = 50 $$ into the power gain formula:</p>\n\n<p>$$ G_P = \\left(\\frac{V_{out}}{V_{in}}\\right)^2 \\cdot \\frac{R_{in}}{R_{out}} = G_V^2 \\cdot \\frac{R_{in}}{R_{out}} $$</p>\n\n<p>So we have:</p>\n\n<p>$$ G_P = 50^2 \\cdot \\frac{100}{400} $$</p>\n\n<p>$$ G_P = 2500 \\cdot 0.25 $$</p>\n\n<p>$$ G_P = 625 $$</p>\n\n<p>Hence, the power gain of the amplifier is <strong>625</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the correct option is:</p>\n\n<p>Option C - 625</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2023,
    "yearKey": "bitsat-2023",
    "difficulty": null
  },
